				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left({p}_{value}>\alpha \right)$$\end{document} as a way of determining equivalence is problematic because it is not possible to conclude that there is no effect when \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${p}_{value}>\alpha$$\end{document} which ignores the statistical power to detect a true effect. This is where effect size, like Cohen’s d, becomes important. One way to assess whether the effect is neglectable is to compare it to some standardized magnitude such as the ratio between the difference of mean values and some joint standard deviation. In the two one sided T-test (TOST)13 procedure, an upper \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
